item.title: FTSE 100 Rises After Stronger US Economic Data Dampens Recession Worries
item.description: The FTSE 100 rose 0.3% as concerns about a global recession declined after a string of U.S. data came in stronger than expected yesterday, and as investors will focus on remarks by central bankers at the ECB forum later.

item.title: Glynn's Take: RBA Remains on Track to Tighten Policy Screws
item.description: The Australian central bank is still likely to be in a hawkish mood because the tamer inflation reading in May was due mostly to a fall in volatile components of the CPI basket.

item.title: Copper Edges Lower After China's Industrial Profits Slump
item.description: A sharp drop in China’s industrial profits added to worries about the nation’s economy and weighed on base metals prices, although low inventories eased the declines.

item.title: Dollar Rises as Strong US Data Should Allow More Rate Increases
item.description: The dollar inched higher in early trade, building on Tuesday’s gains after a set of stronger-than-expected economic data, which should allow the Fed to continue raising interest rates, MUFG said.

item.title: Oil Listless After Slumping on Strong US Data
item.description: Oil prices were little changed following Tuesday’s steep losses, after some strong U.S. economic data heightened the likelihood of more rate hikes from the Fed.

item.title: Volvo Joins Tesla Charging Network
item.description: Volvo has signed an agreement that gives drivers of its electric cars access to Tesla’s network of 12,000 superchargers across the U.S., Canada and Mexico.

item.title: Developed-Market Bond Returns Seen Positive in 2H
item.description: Bond returns in the first half of the year have been positive across developed markets, with the exception of the U.K., and are likely to remain positive in the second half of the year, too, J.P.Morgan said.

item.title: DSM-Firmenich Earnings Seen Hit by Weak Vitamins
item.description: DSM-Firmenich guided for proforma adjusted earnings of up to €1.9 billion in 2023, below the previous year, as it said vitamin prices are expected to remain low until the end of the year.

item.title: German GfK Reading Worse than Expected
item.description: GfK’s forward-looking German consumer sentiment index forecast confidence to tick down to minus 25.4 in July, the first decline in nine months, reflecting a more uncertain climate for household spending as the country’s economic outlook remains bleak.

item.title: Swiss Life on Track for 2024 Targets
item.description: Swiss Life said it was on target to either meet or exceed its 2024 financial goals that include a dividend payout ratio of more than 60%, adjusted return on equity of 10%-12%, and a fee result of up to $1 billion.

item.title: Homebuyers With Short Memories Are Driving Up Prices in Hurricane-Hit Town
item.description: Unfazed by the destruction of Hurricane Ian just nine months ago, luxury-home shoppers are flocking to Naples, Florida

item.title: How Shazam Makes Unique Audio Fingerprints to Identify Songs
item.description: More than 23,000 songs are identified each minute by Shazam and the app has been used over 70 billion times. But while using it is simple, a complex computation makes it possible.

item.title: Blame Swirls in Putin's Inner Circle Following Mutiny
item.description: Long-simmering resentment about the war, along with finger-pointing and recriminations inside the Kremlin, could open a power vacuum that disgruntled advisers could exploit.
